<h1 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Perform Explicit Client Registration with OpenID Federation Trust Chain</strong></h1>



<p>Now your Keycloak is all ready for Explicit Client Registration.</p>



<p>Then, for the Explicit Client Registration request, prepare JWT, which payload is like below:</p>



<pre class="wp-block-code"><code class="">{
    "exp": 1730322632,
    "iat": 1729322632,
    "jwks": {
      "keys": [
        {
          "kid": "47145cad-4d1a-4494-9f17-8de6af81a966",
          "n": "wx_rZVLSeoqomxR8ZYuyW_wNmAlHfI4C2YMwLC1vqp9n59I9XPs40NyaZw37DnZJgAC76kXqJxOhWN9yJ4L7sC87GHd_rcmV5inp0F6nAz8_vQnJv4RlGIOKxsZJ5b-mYzpvmCys_Q2MNOKw4i_2MblhCXN08Wgm60dHUeBBZF5Lpo5BUw6zC-7PReNBd76xo20WXely7we-zONPW4146szwo4knaZseCzpUSbP8hyTE8PgCvFTSF5LVVLL-5CXkdKiywZVZn7svbA2Dk9INAwKnwYXoXptFwxD7F6bYrO94CwSWJjlfl-u38ze9hrVQ14q95U0QglQlrQeGSfeczw", 
          "kty": "RSA",
          "alg": "RS256",
          "use": "sig"
          "e": "AQAB"
        }
      ]
    },
    "aud": "http://localhost:8080/realms/fed01",
    "iss": "http://rp.node.io",
    "sub": "http://rp.node.io",
    "authority_hints": [
      "http://ia.example.com:9090"
    ],
    "metadata": {
    "openid_relying_party": {
      "application_type": "web",
      "contacts": ["ops@rp.node.io"],
      "grant_types": ["authorization_code"],
      "jwks_uri": "https://rp.node.io/jwks.jose",
      "redirect_uris": [
        "https://rp.node.io/openid/callback"
      ], 
      "subject_type": "public"
    }
    }
  }

</code></pre>



<p>Registration request, prepare JWT, which payload is like below. This statement is information about the Relying Party, so both â€œissâ€ and â€œsubâ€ are the Relying Party itself. On the other hand, â€œaudâ€ is the OpenID provider which receives this registration request. The â€œmetadataâ€ is the one about this Relying Party, which includes OIDC/OAuth related ones, such as â€œjwks_uriâ€, â€œredirect_urisâ€. And most importantly â€œauthority_hintsâ€ is a list of authorities who can authorize this Relying Party, usually the list of Intermediate Authorities.</p>



<p>And send a HTTP POST request with the JWT above:</p>



<pre class="wp-block-code"><code class="">POST /realms/fed01/oidc-federation/op/fedreg HTTP/1.1
Host: localhost:8080
</code></pre>



<p>Finally,&nbsp; check if a new client is created on admin console like below:</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXd6K_Ku4mXyl8I10oWDz1v4jIAgTHZZU41y_zseL3pcnpoUQRMa1wLL8EPCHg6aJEoPIkkZ1VEXnD9A5h4yxSDarwqfq7X9AlQNeEbsE53c2pmnh90rXhC7H_wPhKaWX1Itnqv0P9INnyTZ4Y-vUzI?key=jskB4iDnEtwCBmCgcApLTfra" alt="new console" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image"><img decoding="async" src="https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXdMPDcxDKDoHk517WetJBSTWLeu7g_uySJYnuz0zTkT8ntHvyW9GgonAN0_F9Vxnx1A23D-LvsiBIwux1vaF3QuB3m2wVM4K-bxGRicGHkq7vsoqfvqnNk_yg0HfOsW7bnpOMDeSFESQ8X_TBoE7Hs?key=jskB4iDnEtwCBmCgcApLTfra" alt="Explicit Client" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></figure>



<p>As a result, you can see here the client you have just created by Explicit Client Registration.</p>



<h1 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Conclusion</strong></h1>



<p>In this article, I explained how to build trust between a 3-rd party Relying Party and Keycloak as an OpenID Provider with OpenID Federation Trust Chain.</p>



<p>Currently in the Keycloak community, <a href="https://github.com/keycloak/kc-sig-fapi">OAuth-SIG</a> (a group whose activity is mainly supporting OIDC/OAuth and its related security features to Keycloak) discusses how to enhance&nbsp; Keycloak to build the Digital Identity Wallet ecosystem, for which we believe OpenID Federation plays a crucial role and we are taking an initiative to include the OpenID Federation functionality into Keycloak.</p>

